<p>Of these, [12] is the least certain and based on some sort of reason or evidence. Be careful to not confuse this meaning of â€˜shouldâ€™ with obligation. [13] has the flavor of promise or spur or the moment decision, while [14] is a planned action.</p>

<h2 id="inferences-about-past-events">Inferences about past events</h2>

<p>If you see the results of an event in the past, you can make an inference about the event that caused what youâ€™re currently observing. This structure causes the most confusion!</p>

<p>[15] <em>The salesperson looks awful this morning, he must have gone out drinking with clients last night.</em><br />
[16] <em>He definitely has a hangover, he must not have drunk any pickle juice.</em></p>

<p>The key point to remember is that â€˜must have doneâ€™ can <strong>never</strong> refer to an obligation. It refers to an event that happened in the past with results that can be observed now.</p>

<p>One last gotcha is that â€˜must not haveâ€™ isnâ€™t about prohibition or inability:</p>

<p>[17] <em>I couldnâ€™t go to the concert since I got sick.</em><br />
